entry.title: Add CookieEncryptionManager interface to network service.
entry.content:
This CL adds a new method on the NetworkService mojo interface

called SetCookieEncryptionProvider which allows setting of a

custom cookie encryption provider to work with OSCrypt async.



Once SetCookieEncryptionProvider is called with a provider,

then any network contexts created that have `enable_encrypted_cookies`

set to true, will use this cookie encryption provider rather

than the default one provided by //components/cookie_config.



Tests are added to both services_unittests and also

content_browsertests to verify the functionality of the new

method.



Future CLs will wire this into //chrome and add tests for

backwards and forwards compatibility.

entry.title: Reland "Android: Fail early for wrong ABI"
entry.content:
Fixes:

- Skip webview scripts from the 32/64-bit check as they can work as the

webview provider even if the manifest marks it as 32-bit only.



Original CL: https://crrev.com/c/5074739



Previously on 64-bit only devices (e.g. pixel 7) apks and bundles

containing 32-bit chrome can be installed and a RuntimeException will

occur on startup. It is easy to miss the RuntimeException and mistakenly

assume the failure is due to some other exception in the logcat.



This CL checks whether the application defines android:use32bitAbi and

prevents installation on 64-bit only devices if the value is true (or

'0xffffffff' from aapt.Dump). Link to the native libs doc for choosing

the correct 64-bit chrome target name.

entry.title: Fix FileSelectListenerImpl dangling raw_ptr
entry.content:
What's happening here is that the chooser may drop its reference to

the listener, then when the chooser is destroyed, it doesn't call

ResetOwner. If the WebContentsDelegate keeps a reference to the

listener longer than the lifetime of the chooser, then when the

listener is destroyed, it will have a dangling ptr to the chooser.



A new test is included, which performs this sequence of events

and fails without this fix.



Switching to a WeakPtr makes this easier to reason about and avoids

the need for manually clearing the pointer. A WeakPtr is needed

anyway for task posting.



While we're here, FileChooserImpl is a WebContentsObserver just so

it can clear out its RenderFrameHost ptr. We can store the RFH's id

instead.

entry.title: [iOS] Make sure the search for a provider completes properly
entry.content:
The RunSearchPipeline loop used to search for the proper provider

to serve suggestions for a given field was getting stuck and never

properly completing, due to pending queries never being executed.



RunSearchPipeline relies on the completion block to be called in

order for the next iteration in the search to be executed, so if

the completion block never gets executed, the loop never completes

its search for providers. In the password mamnager's case, the

pending queries will be the ones calling the completion blocks.



In PasswordFormManager, a mechanism using "autofills_left_" used

to avoid getting infinite loops was causing an early exit, which

was also leaving the form queries hanging, never to be completed,

and never calling the completion blocks, so the autofill provider

(for addresses, credit cards, etc) could never get set.



This CL makes sure form extraction isn't attempted twice from

checkIfSuggestionsAvailableForForm for the same frame, so that

completion blocks can be executed immediately instead of being

stored in a list of pending queries if we already know what the

form contains.

entry.title: Cap the number of objects checked in AXObjectCacheImpl::CheckTreeIsUpdated
entry.content:
AXObjectCacheImpl::CheckTreeIsUpdated verifies that we have correctly

updated the accessibility tree after an update. Recently*, a second set

of checks was added to verify that all dirty bits to update properties

or children have been cleared. If DCHECK is enabled, each set of these

checks examines all of the items in objects_, which can amount to a

lot of work given a very large accessibility tree. In addition, tree

updates can occur frequently, increasing the amount of work done.



As an example, ChromeVoxEditingTest.GiantTextAreaPerformance on a

debug bot results in CheckTreeIsUpdated being called at least 20

times with objects_ having over 38,000 objects in it. Prior to the

second set of checks, this test was somewhat flaky. The addition of

the second set of checks resulted in reliable failures due to

timeouts.



One solution is to not call CheckTreeIsUpdated so frequently; another

is to cap the number of objects checked. This change uses the latter

approach, setting the maximum number of objects to check each time

to 10,000. With this limit, the test is slow, but seems to reliably

run to successful completion.



*Commit history of the second set of checks:

- Originally landed in crrev.com/c/4873421

- Relanded in crrev.com/c/5019353

- Re-relanded in crrev.com/c/5038755

entry.title: [dPWA] Fix DialogDelegate UAF by delaying "this" destruction
entry.content:
crbug.com/1506302 brought to light an UAF in the DialogDelegate code

which can be triggered by running a cancel_callback_ that

deletes the delegate itself. On the web_applications/ side,

the UAF was tracked down to the

WebAppUninstallDialogDelegateView, which might sometimes have

a ScopedKeepAlive that deletes itself as part of callback,

leading to the deletion of the delegate itself.



This CL attempts to fix that by posting the ScopedKeepAlive reset to the SequencedTaskRunner to be deleted in the next message loop, making it async enough so that the current DialogDelegate has ample time to clean itself up.



A larger more robust fix would be to have DialogDelegate support

callbacks that delete itself.

entry.title: v4l2/stateless: Poll for buffer events
entry.content:
Buffers that are done being used will notify the file

descriptor. As V4L2 is asynchronous this is a way to

know when a buffer is completely done being decoded into.

By waiting on this event the decoder can be notified

that a buffer is ready to be passed off to the display.



Once the event has occurred a task is posted. This avoids

needing to have a separate thread to do the dequing and

having to handle concurrency.

entry.title: Don't process-isolate sandboxed iframes inside extensions.
entry.content:
Process-isolating sandboxed iframes within extension pages will cause

the content in data: url frames to lose access to extension resources.

Process isolation for such iframes is desirable (to block extension

API access, etc. see Issue 1376636), but we'll need to allow the new

process to have extension resource access before doing so, to preserve

compatibility.



This CL disallows process-isolation for sandboxed frames which have

an opaque origin with an extension origin precursor, to avoid these

compatibility issues. This ensures that sandboxed data: URLs,

about:srcdoc documents, and same-origin extension URLs stay in the

extension process, while still allowing web URLs and cross-extension

URLs to load in OOPIFs.



In the future, when a plan exists for moving existing

extensions to the process-isolated sandboxed iframe behavior, the

code added here can be amended or removed.



- ExtensionBrowserTest.RSSParseFeed*

- ProcessMapBrowserTest

.IsPrivilegedExtensionProcess_SandboxedExtensionFrame

- ProcessMapBrowserTest

.CanHostContextType_SandboxedExtensionFrame

entry.title: Support background trigger registrations
entry.content:
Looks for trigger registrations headers when receiving background data

in `NotifyBackgroundRegistrationData` and process them.



Triggers received via background registration will also be deferred

if some source registrations for the last navigation are ongoing.



In `NotifyNavigationRegistrationData`, obtain the registration before

retrieving the header to process.



Another side-effect is that it will now log audit issues when

non-processed headers are received through foreground navigation or

fenced frame. Before it was only looking for a source header, therefore

silently ignoring trigger headers. Now, if a trigger header is present,

it will still be ignored, but an audit issue will be emitted.

entry.title: [1 of 3] Renames ios test runner flags to reflect usage.

`--xcode-parallelization` does not imply parallelization and instead

means use xcodebuild runner. It is renamed to `--xcodebuild-sim-runner`

to match the corresponding flag for device.



`--shards` is too easily confused with swarming shards. It will be

renamed to `--clones` to reflect how many clones of the target

iOS simulator will be used to simultaneously run tests on a machine.



A followup CL will need to be submitted to fully remove old flags once the internal references to those flags are removed.

entry.title: ui: add accelerator registration to WebDialogDelegate
entry.content:
Currently, the only way to register accelerators is to override

GetAccelerators() and AcceleratorPressed(). There are two clients that

do this - one registers a single accelerator, the other registers about

a dozen. It would be good if it was possible to use WebDialogDelegate

and have accelerators without extending it, and ultimately allow for

less subclasses of this class.



This change adds a new method called RegisterAccelerator() to

WebDialogDelegate, and adds an internal accelerator table to

WebDialogDelegate. It also adds default logic to the class to use that

table to implement GetAccelerators() and AcceleratorPressed(). Future

CLs will migrate both existing clients to RegisterAccelerator(), then

remove GetAccelerators() and AcceleratorPressed() and remove both the

current client subclasses that override these methods.

entry.title: Revert "Exclude HeuristicSource::kLegacy from non-active patterns"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 440828a02e56dcecd43896676a0c765db907c3b9.



Reason for revert: Likely culprit of failing autofill tests, e.g. https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chrome/builders/ci/linux-chromeos-chrome/37601



Original change's description:

> Exclude HeuristicSource::kLegacy from non-active patterns

>

> A HeuristicSource describes a mechanism to get heuristic predictions,

> which is currently either ML or regexes. Due to pattern provider,

> which can provide different regex definitions, "regexes" is split

> further into different PatternSources.

>

> The active HeuristicSource defines the mechanism that's used to compute

> the fields' heuristic types used in production (the one that will

> influence the overall type used for filling).

>

> The non-active HeuristicSources are defined as the set of all available

> HeuristicSources, except the active HeuristicSource. The PatternSources

> among these non-active HeuristicSources are used to compute shadow predictions for the kAutofillParsingPatternProvider experiment.

>

> What exactly all available HeuristicSources are depends on build flags

> and feature flags, and this CL changes that definition.

>

> Generally:

> - HeuristicSource::kMachineLearning is only available when

> kAutofillModelPredictions is enabled.

> - HeuristicSource::kDefault, HeuristicSource::kExperimental and

> HeuristicSource::kNextGen are only available in Chrome branded builds

> when kAutofillParsingPatternProvider is enabled.

> - HeuristicSource::kLegacy is always available.

>

> This CL removes HeuristicSource::kLegacy from the available patterns in

> Chrome branded builds when kAutofillParsingPatternProvider is enabled.

> This is desirable for a few reasons:

> - Chrome branded builds with kAutofillParsingPatternProvider are not

> using the kLegacy patterns, not even for shadow metrics. They are

> intended to be lower-quality regexes for non-Chrome branded builds.

> - Since they are currently part of the non-active HeuristicSources,

> they take up additional computational resources during parsing.

>
